This problme can be solved with brute force / sliding window/ prefix sums.

Here we are using prefix sums approach.

We use a hash map to store how many times this prefix has repeated and use this to calculated the total no of sub arrays that can form K
For each index, we calculate the running prefix sum current. 
Then we calculate current - k to check whether we have seen an older prefix sum that can be removed to make the current subarray sum equal to k. 
After checking, we store/update the current prefix sum in the map because it may be needed for future subarrays.


class solution{
    public int subArraySum(int[] nums, int k)
    {

    int current = 0;
    int result = 0;

    Map<Integer, Integer> prefixSums = new HashMap<>();

    prefixSums.add(0,1); //we have already seen zero sum once

    for( int i : nums)
    {
      current += i;
      int diff = current - k;

      //now we calculate the result i.e. no of times this could have appeared
      result  += prefixSums.getOrDefault(diff,  0);

      prefixSum.put(current, prefixSum.getOrDefault(current , 0)+1);

      }

      return result;
      }
